text: Believable? No. And that was the point. Murphy effectively didn't survive. When Robocop first appears he is essentially a robot with some human flesh used as stock. But through the story we realize the man Murphy still existed in there somewhere in some fashion. It was that journey and Murphy's realization of who he was and his acclimation to what he is now that made the character worth it. This 'ghost in the machine' trope seems to have been totally eliminated.

text: Every one of you chanting "it's new technology!  stop whining!" are completely missing the point of the original.  1987 Robocop was 95% social commentary about corrupt and legitimate authority, the wealthy 1%, disposing of something when it breaks down instead of trying to fix it, labour unions ruining the U.S.A., greed, and many other topics.  It had Biblical references, morality, and artistic direction. This is Hollywood garbage made to draw in the lowest common denominator for ticket sales.

text: While I would say its little unfair to judge a movie that has not been released yet, I think the better point to attempt to make here is that remakes are important to keep a movie alive; in principle they are basically "updates" to pre-existing movies to conform them to current generation story writing mechanics and special effects standards.  This way the rising generation and audience can enjoy the classics on their level without having to go watch "some old movie their parents say is good."

author: John Crum

text: Because a thing is a remake doesn't make it bad. A thing being bad makes it bad. A thing being a remake doesn't make it "too lame to write anything new," (although that happens and it sucks) but often a remake happens because a writer or director loved the original so much that they want to present it to newer audiences.

text: Standing on it's own two (robot) feet, this movie is worth watching. It's not hyper/ultra violent. It's not campy. Rather than trying to replicate the original movie with updated effects, this RoboCop is worth watching due to it's more thoughtful approach to a man being changed into a man/machine hybrid against his will, dependent on machines to keep living. The same machines that detract from his humanity also give him the means to hunt down those responsible for his new state of being and give him the edge necessary to protect others from criminals to a far greater degree than he was previously capable of as a regular cop.

text: I was a kid when verhoven's original came out, and I still watch it now. This remake wasn't terrible, it definitely tried to tackle some philosophical elements of the man/machine element of the character, but it wasn't executed very well. Verhoven made a tragic, satirical and gory technological crime fighting action movie, whereas the remake just didn't know which stance to take. I don't say these things based on nostalgia, but remaking something as unique and memorable as Robocop was never going to be easy.
